Marketplace (agents + MCP servers) and how usage is measured
The Marketplace is how we avoid “tribal knowledge.” It’s where we can discover what agents and MCP servers exist, who owns them, what they are good for, and how to use them.

Entries are presented as cards with the essentials (name, owner/maintainer, address, version, and optional icon). Clicking into an entry opens a full details view: what it does, when to use it, how it works at a high level, where the Bitbucket repo lives, and for MCP servers, which tools are exposed.

Phase 1 also introduces usage visibility. Each marketplace entry can expose a lightweight usage reporting mechanism: whenever an agent or MCP server is called, it can notify the portal (either directly, or via the gateway/orchestrator layer) so the portal increments a usage counter and records “last used” information. This makes adoption measurable, helps users pick the right tool (sorting/filtering by popularity becomes meaningful), and helps owners understand whether their work is being used.

Like everything else in Phase 1, marketplace data is stored in the DB and follows the ownership model: users can delete or manage entries they own; admins can manage any entry.

