Build and Deploy (agents and MCP servers) with infra governance
Phase 1 makes “creating something” and “running something” first-class workflows, but it does so in a way that respects enterprise constraints.

Build Agent is presented as a guided creation flow. We choose a name, and the system creates a new Bitbucket repo from a standard template that already includes Python code structure, .env scaffolding, Dockerfile, and Helm chart. Placeholder fields like __appname__ are replaced automatically. Permissions are applied so everyone can collaborate via PRs, but only the owner can merge (admins can override). At the same time, the system creates a multibranch pipeline so the repo immediately has a standardized CI path.

Deploy Agent is where infra integration becomes explicit. The portal does not deploy charts directly; instead, it triggers the infra deployment mechanism with the user’s identity context. The deployment request includes enough information for infra to deploy into the correct namespace/project and to apply the correct quota/policy. Phase 1 intentionally documents an open decision here: deployments can be triggered either by calling an infra API server or by triggering an infra-owned Jenkins job. The portal supports both patterns; the organization chooses the one that best matches existing guardrails and ownership boundaries.

The portal also introduces lifecycle rules that keep the cluster clean: versions that are not main/master/release are treated as temporary by default and automatically deleted after a configured TTL (for example 10 days). That TTL is configured centrally and presented in the UI so the behavior is predictable.

After deployment succeeds, the portal records the deployment in the DB so it appears in the marketplace and in “My Deployments.” Users can delete their own deployments from the UI, and admins can delete anything.



